<p>In <a href="/wiki/Mathematical_analysis" title="Mathematical analysis">mathematical analysis</a>, <b>Euler's identity</b>, named after <a href="/wiki/Leonhard_Euler" title="Leonhard Euler">Leonhard Euler</a>, is the equation</p>
<dl>
<dd><img class="tex" alt="e^{i \pi} + 1 = 0, \,\!" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/2/c/c2cc760385a6ef275c61dc193e6ceaea.png" /></dd>
</dl>
<p>where</p>
<dl>
<dd><img class="tex" alt="e\,\!" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/6/0/460a1940ceddf45878d2e095af31128a.png" /> is <a href="/wiki/E_(mathematical_constant)" title="E (mathematical constant)">Euler's number</a>, the base of the <a href="/wiki/Natural_logarithm" title="Natural logarithm">natural logarithm</a>,</dd>
<dd><img class="tex" alt="i\,\!" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/7/9/a796b40d92e81ae190a1e4f4e2a2c3ed.png" /> is the <a href="/wiki/Imaginary_unit" title="Imaginary unit">imaginary unit</a>, one of the two <a href="/wiki/Complex_number" title="Complex number">complex numbers</a> whose square is negative one (the other is <img class="tex" alt="-i\,\!" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/d/2/9d21cfd11a9b9b2b152de3fd863d9e29.png" />), and</dd>
<dd><img class="tex" alt="\pi\,\!" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/0/6/e06a022b86322d6ee502b6760a0ed4ec.png" /> is <a href="/wiki/Pi" title="Pi">pi</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Ratio" title="Ratio">ratio</a> of the circumference of a circle to its diameter.</dd>
</dl>
<p>Euler's identity is also sometimes called <b>Euler's equation</b>.</p>
